## **Measuring Data**

The amount of data that can be stored on a storage device (like SD cards, USB sticks, hard drives and RAM) uses a system similar to the metric system:

| Units of Data |  |  |
| ----- | :---- | :---- |
| Measurement | Is equal to… | Can store… |
| Bit | Binary digit (1/8th of a byte) | 0 or 1 |
| Byte | Base Unit (8 bits) | One character (h, k, ?, \*) |
| Kilobyte (KB) | 1,000 Bytes  | Enough to store ½ page of text |
| Megabyte (MB) | 100,000 Bytes (1000 KB) | Roughly 1 min of music |
| Gigabyte (GB) | 1,000,000,000 Bytes (1000 MB) | A small game or a large app |
| Terabyte (TB) | 1,000,000,000,000 Bytes (1000 GB) | 10 4K movies  |

Fun fact\! You may see outdated sources saying that a KB is equal to 1024 bytes. This was partly due to marketing baloney, and partly due to measuring using powers of 2 (2^10 \= 1024). Today, a Kilobyte is 1000 bytes, while 1024 bytes is called a Kibibyte.
